snippet.textDisplay: Here's a guy that won the world champion by beating Klitschko. Then battled depression, drugs, and alcohol, gained a bunch of weight, fought the Bronze Bomber after two tune-up fights, and displayed the heart of a champion by getting up after being clobbered by Wilder's bone-crushing right as if he rose from the dead, then takes the re-match, against all the pundits who said he would lose, only to destroy Wilder in an mouth dropping exhibit ever witnessed in the boxing game. He praised Jesus afterward, our Lord and Savior. And then sings a song. This man--Tyson Fury---made boxing exciting again. Ali was the greatest of all time, no doubt. Fans loved him, and some did not. But he made boxing what it is today with big paydays. Mike Tyson rose out of Streets of Brooklyn and found himself in the camp of Cus D'amato, and boxing fans were on the edge of their seats as boxing was reinvented. After Ali and Mike Tyson were in the history books, boxing was boring. NOW there's Tyson Fury and fans are once again on the edge of their seats. You may love him or you may hate him. But he is the WBC Champion of the world and nobody can deny that he beat the baddest man on the planet to earn it.
